=== Strings

Morloc supports multi-line strings and string interpolation.

String interpolation uses the `#{...}` syntax. The expression inside the braces
must evaluate to a `Str`:

[source, morloc]
----
helloYou you = "hello #{you}"
cn = "你知道得太多了" -- strings support unicode
----

String interpolation works with any expression that returns a string.

Multi-line strings use triple quotes. Leading indentation common to all lines is
stripped:

[source, morloc]
----
longString =
  """
  this is a long
  string
  """
----

For triple-quoted long string, spacing is trimmed by applying the following 3 rules in order:
  1. Initial spaces up to and including the first newline are removed
  2. Terminal spaces up to and including the final newline are removed
  3. All leading spaces are trimmed by the number of leading spaces in the line with the fewest leading spaces

This allows you to write blocks of text with natural indentation. The `longString` above evaluates to:

----
this is a long
string
----

Triple quotes can also be used to avoid issues with internal quotations. In the
one-line case, they are equivalent to single-quoted strings:

[source, morloc]
----
-- triple-quoted strings can contain internal quotes
quoted = """you can use "internal quotes" freely"""
----

Single and double quote are both support and are identical:

[source, morloc]
----
quotedS = """you can use "internal quotes" freely"""
quotedD = '''you can use "internal quotes" freely'''
----
